title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory Model 1903 Mark I Rifle
postcontent: his is an excellent Springfield Armory Model 1903 Mark I Rifle in .30-06 as arsenal overhauled during or before WWII. The serial number is 1107926, indicating it was manufactured in 1919. The Mark I was developed for the Pedersen Device, which was an attempt to introduce a semi-automatic rifle on a emergency basis at the end of WWI. The war ended before the Pedersen Devices could be fielded but production of Mark I's continued into 1919 before the program was scrapped (as were the majority of the Pedersen Devices). The barrel is the original installed on this rifle and is a Springfield Barrel dated September 1919. The barrel is superb with a mirror bore, strong rifling and it gauges at just over 0! This will a very accurate shooter. The stock is a Type 2 "S" Stock that was manufactured by Springfield Armory as a replacement stock and has the finger grooves and two reinforcing bolts. There is a "J" stamp in the magazine cutoff recess and a sans serif circle "P" firing proof on the bottom of the wrist. The stock has normal handling dings and scratches but no cracks. This rifle was covered inside and out with cosmoline when I got it, to include the stock, and I don't think this rifle was every issued given the lack of wear in the barrel and on the hardware. All parts retain the majority of the arsenal gray-green parkerized finish, which was done during overhaul either just before or during WWII. There are no post-war arsenal cartouches. The hand guard is also a Springfield Type 9, 1st Variation convex that has handling and storage dings but no cracks. Has the original Type 2 Lower Barrel Band with sling swivel that has nearly 100% of the reparkerized finish. The milled Upper Barrel Band with bayonet lug and stacking swivel likewise has nearly 100% of the reparkerized finish. Has a milled Rear Sling Swivel Assembly. Front Sight is a Model 1905 Type 2, 2nd Variation. The Butt Plate is an early Type 3A fully checkered with trap door. The milled Springfield Trigger Guard and Floor Plate also have nearly 100% of the reparkerized finish. The bolt is an excellent bent bolt Brown & Sharp subcontracted bolt that also has nearly all of its parkerized finish and is marked "B&S" over an Ordnance Bomb on the bolt handle. Has Type 1 Serif Magazine Cutoff. This rifle functions perfectly and will be an awesome shooter given the barrel. This rifle is C&R eligible. Please let me know if you have any questions or would like additional photos posted. Please also check my other listings for antique military weapons. I accept Visa and MasterCard and charge NO FEES. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  POLISH RADOM MAG-98 9MM  POLISH EAGLE PISTOL
postcontent:
Legendary Polish Special Forces Mag98 pistol, Used Surplus Condition,
Shows signs of use, shoots and groups great, great modern 9mm, very rare..
Accepts Beretta and Taurus mags..

The Polish MAG 98 9mm /9x19 NATO caliber pistol is an improved variation of the original Polish MAG95. 
It was produced for the Polish Special Forces, Border Guard and Prison Guard (Straż Więzienna) in the 1990's. 
Made in the Z.M. Lucznik factory 11 at Radom Poland. 

These fine pistols feature a ambidextrous decocker safety, steel slide, alloy frame, and serrated trigger guard front strap.
In 1996 the Mag 98 was evaluated for adoption purposes by the Polish Army. It had advantages over its competition such as 
better reliability, durability and safety (better protection against accidental discharge, when dropped). 

Although the quality was deemed superior,  the MAG 98 was rejected by the Army because the frame was slightly larger
than  the contract qualifications called for. That was a shame because most service members prefered it and in fact 
the pistol has a good reputation among users: It is considered a precise, well balanced and durable weapon 
and its mass leads to good stability during firing. 

This double/single action pistol comes with ONE 15rd magazine.

Soft-point bullets are less common than hollow points, due to the slower expansion and greater penetration, but they fill roles that hollow points do not. In some cases the reduced expansion is desired, so that more penetration is achieved before the bullet begins the rapid deceleration caused by expansion. In other cases, the smooth, rounded profile typical of a soft-point bullet is preferred over the concave tip of a hollow point, because the latter tends to suffer failure to feed malfunctions in certain magazine-fed firearms. Many of the more modern magazine-fed firearms were expressly designed to feed hollow points reliably, but many older and military-derived designs were not

For ANYONE who know ANYTHING about tactical and defensive shooting, Massad Ayoob's assessment is legendary.

Massad Ayoob is internationally known as a renowned author, columnist, and instructor on the subject of firearms and self-defense. In his book, "The Gun Digest Book of Combat Handgunnery", Ayoob writes the G30 "may be the most accurate pistol that Glock makes." In his personal experience, the stock G30 with factory ammo is capable of under 1.0-inch groups for 5 shots at 25 yards from off the bench, performing better than the Gen3 G21 or G36. The G30 is freakishly accurate for a combat pistol with a 3.78 inch barrel. 

"Mas wrote a comprehensive review of the Glock 30 that was published in the American Handgunner 1998 Combat Annual, titled "Fist Full of .45". The impressive result he obtained on the firing range with the first G30 he received for evaluation is very interesting reading. After firing three boxes of ammo to break in the pistol, Ayoob shot a 1-3/16" group of 5 shots at a measured range of 25 yards from a righthand barricade standing position using Federal 230gr HydraShok HP factory ammo. The best three of five shots were just 3/8" apart. He was so favorably impressed by the G30 that he couldn't resist the temptation to buy the test pistol for his personal use."
